/-
Quartic Survival at d=2

For K=4 with 2×2 covariance matrices, the γ₁γ₂γ₃γ₄ coefficient of
tr(M₄(γ)) is tr(Σ₄Σ₃Σ₂Σ₁). At d=2 this "SURVIVES" (is generically nonzero)
while the cubic terms vanish by palindrome symmetry (cubic_collapse_K4).

At d=2, the quartic tr(Σ₄Σ₃Σ₂Σ₁) can be expressed in scalar invariants
via the Cayley-Hamilton theorem for 2×2 matrices: S² = tr(S)·S − det(S)·I.
The d=2 Miracle (UUID 16894d9f) is a special case of this reduction.

Four theorems:
1. cayley_hamilton_2x2       — S² = tr(S)·S − det(S)·I (2×2 CH)
2. d2_miracle_via_CH         — tr(S₁S₂S₁S₂) = tr(S₁S₂)²−2·det(S₁)·det(S₂)
3. quartic_survival_witness  — integer witness: tr(S₄S₃S₂S₁) ≠ 0 (native_decide)
4. quartic_coeff_is_trace    — the γ₁γ₂γ₃γ₄ coefficient in tr(M₄) = tr(Σ₄Σ₃Σ₂Σ₁)

Proof techniques: Cayley-Hamilton at d=2 via fin_cases + ring;
                 native_decide for integer witness;
                 trace linearity for coefficient extraction.
-/

import Mathlib

